and also

'''Mazeltov''' is a [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] word meaning "good luck" but is often used in place of "congratulations."  
The expression comes from the [[Akkadian language]] ''manzaltu, mazzaztum,'' "position of a star," from ''izuzzu,'' "to stand." This descended to the [[Mishnaic Hebrew]] ''mazzāl'', meaning "[[constellation]]" or "[[destiny]]." Adding the word ṭôb, meaning "good," a direct English translation would be "good destiny" or "good [[fortune]]." [http://www.answers.com/mazel+tov&r=67]

Like other [[blessings]] it is often said frequently and sometimes loudly at [[Jewish]] [[weddings]] as well as [[Bar Mitzvah]]s.  It is commonly used within the Jewish community.  In colloquial languange, "Mazel tov" is sometimes said sarcastically when congratulations are not appropriate or due.

